{"tag":"section","attrib":{"id":"id5236ff5e-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6","identifier":"/us/usc/t28/s134"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"134"},"text":"§ 134.","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":" Tenure and residence of district judges","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{"id":"id5236ff5f-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6","identifier":"/us/usc/t28/s134/a"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"a"},"text":"(a)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" The district judges shall hold office during good behavior.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{"id":"id5236ff60-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6","identifier":"/us/usc/t28/s134/b"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"b"},"text":"(b)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" Each district judge, except in the District of Columbia, the Southern District of New York, and the Eastern District of New York, shall reside in the district or one of the districts for which he is appointed. Each district judge of the Southern District of New York and the Eastern District of New York may reside within 20 miles of the district to which he or she is appointed.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{"id":"id5236ff61-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6","identifier":"/us/usc/t28/s134/c"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"c"},"text":"(c)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" If the public interest and the nature of the business of a district court require that a district judge should maintain his abode at or near a particular place for holding court in the district or within a particular part of the district the judicial council of the circuit may so declare and may make an appropriate order. If the district judges of such a district are unable to agree as to which of them shall maintain his abode at or near the place or within the area specified in such an order the judicial council of the circuit may decide which of them shall do so.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"sourceCredit","attrib":{"id":"id5236ff62-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":"(","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1948-06-25/ch646"},"text":"June 25, 1948, ch. 646","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/62/896"},"text":"62 Stat. 896","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1949-08-03/ch387/s2/b/1"},"text":"Aug. 3, 1949, ch. 387, § 2(b)(1)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/63/495"},"text":"63 Stat. 495","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1954-02-10/ch6/s2/b/13/a"},"text":"Feb. 10, 1954, ch. 6, § 2(b)(13)(a)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/68/12"},"text":"68 Stat. 12","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/86/3/s9/c"},"text":"Pub. L. 86–3, § 9(c)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1959-03-18"},"text":"Mar. 18, 1959","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/73/8"},"text":"73 Stat. 8","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/87/36/s2/e/3"},"text":"Pub. L. 87–36, § 2(e)(3)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1961-05-19"},"text":"May 19, 1961","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/75/83"},"text":"75 Stat. 83","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/89/571/s1"},"text":"Pub. L. 89–571, § 1","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1966-09-12"},"text":"Sept. 12, 1966","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/80/764"},"text":"80 Stat. 764","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/92/208/s3/e"},"text":"Pub. L. 92–208, § 3(e)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1971-12-18"},"text":"Dec. 18, 1971","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/85/742"},"text":"85 Stat. 742","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/104/317/tVI/s607"},"text":"Pub. L. 104–317, title VI, § 607","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1996-10-19"},"text":"Oct. 19, 1996","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/110/3860"},"text":"110 Stat. 3860","children":[],"tail":".)"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"notes","attrib":{"type":"uscNote","id":"id5236ff63-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"historicalAndRevision","id":"id5236ff64-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Historical and Revision Notes","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Based on title 28, U.S.C., 1940 ed., § 1 and ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t48/s863"},"text":"section 863 of title 48","children":[],"tail":", U.S.C., 1940 ed., Territories and Insular Possessions ("},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1900-04-12/ch191/s34"},"text":"Apr. 12, 1900, ch. 191, § 34","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/31/84"},"text":"31 Stat. 84","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1911-03-03/ch231/s1"},"text":"Mar. 3, 1911, ch. 231, § 1","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/36/1087"},"text":"36 Stat. 1087","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1913-01-07"},"text":"Jan. 7, 1913","children":[],"tail":"; ch. 6, "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/37/648"},"text":"37 Stat. 648","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1914-07-30/ch216"},"text":"July 30, 1914, ch. 216","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/38/580"},"text":"38 Stat. 580","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1917-03-02/ch145/s41"},"text":"Mar. 2, 1917, ch. 145, § 41","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/39/965"},"text":"39 Stat. 965","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1921-03-04/ch161/s1"},"text":"Mar. 4, 1921, ch. 161, § 1","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/41/1412"},"text":"41 Stat. 1412","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1922-09-14/ch306/s1"},"text":"Sept. 14, 1922, ch. 306, § 1","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/42/837"},"text":"42 Stat. 837","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1938-03-26/ch51/s2"},"text":"Mar. 26, 1938, ch. 51, § 2","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/52/118"},"text":"52 Stat. 118","children":[],"tail":")."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Section consolidates the last paragraph of ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s1"},"text":"section 1 of title 28","children":[],"tail":", U.S.C., 1940 ed., with portions of "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t48/s863"},"text":"section 863 of title 48","children":[],"tail":", U.S.C., 1940 ed., with changes in phraseology necessary to effect consolidation."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Provisions of ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s1"},"text":"section 1 of title 28","children":[],"tail":", U.S.C., 1940 ed., relating to the number of judges in the various districts are incorporated in "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s133"},"text":"section 133 of this title","children":[],"tail":"."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"A portion of ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t48/s863"},"text":"section 863 of title 48","children":[],"tail":", U.S.C., 1940 ed., is retained in said title 48. For remainder of section 863, see Distribution Table."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"The exception in subsection (b) “except in the District of Columbia” conforms with the recent decision in ","children":[{"tag":"i","attrib":{},"text":"U.S. ex. rel. Laughlin v. Eicher","children":[],"tail":", 1944, 56 F.Supp. 972, holding that residence requirement of "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s1"},"text":"section 1 of title 28","children":[],"tail":", U.S.C., 1940 ed., did not apply to district judges in the District of Columbia. (See reviser’s note under "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s44"},"text":"section 44 of this title","children":[],"tail":".)"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"The clause in said last paragraph of ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s1"},"text":"section 1 of title 28","children":[],"tail":" providing that any district judge, who violates the residence requirement, shall be deemed guilty of a high misdemeanor, was omitted. This penalty provision was attached to the residence requirement at the time of compilation of the Revised Statutes of 1878, although it is apparent that Congress only intended that the penalty should be invoked upon the unauthorized practice of law. See "},{"tag":"i","attrib":{},"text":"U.S. ex. rel. Laughlin v. Eicher","children":[],"tail":", supra, in which an outline of the history of said "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s1"},"text":"section 1 of title 28","children":[],"tail":" is given."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"role":"crossHeading","topic":"editorialNotes","id":"id5236ff65-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"b","attrib":{},"text":"Editorial Notes","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"amendments","id":"id5236ff66-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Amendments","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1996—Subsec. (b). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/104/317"},"text":"Pub. L. 104–317","children":[],"tail":" inserted “the Southern District of New York, and the Eastern District of New York,” after “the District of Columbia,” and inserted “Each district judge of the Southern District of New York and the Eastern District of New York may reside within 20 miles of the district to which he or she is appointed.” at end."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1971—Subsec. (c). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/92/208"},"text":"Pub. L. 92–208","children":[],"tail":" struck out provision requiring that one of the district judges for the Eastern District of Louisiana reside in East Baton Rouge Parish, Louisiana."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1966—Subsec. (a). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/89/571"},"text":"Pub. L. 89–571","children":[],"tail":" struck out provisions which excepted district judges in Puerto Rico from tenure during good behavior and which instead set eight-year terms for them to be served until their successors were appointed and qualified."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1961—Subsec. (c). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/87/36"},"text":"Pub. L. 87–36","children":[],"tail":" required the residence of one of the district judges for the Eastern District of Louisiana to be in East Baton Rouge Parish, Louisiana."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1959—Subsec. (a). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/86/3"},"text":"Pub. L. 86–3","children":[],"tail":" struck out provisions which limited district judges in Hawaii to a term of six years."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1954—Subsecs. (a) and (b) reenacted without change by act ","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1954-02-10"},"text":"Feb. 10, 1954","children":[],"tail":"."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsec. (c). Act ","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1954-02-10"},"text":"Feb. 10, 1954","children":[],"tail":", substituted entirely new provisions giving the judicial council of the circuit the authority to determine residence of district judges when it is in the public interest and the nature of the business of the district court necessitates the presence of a judge at or near a particular place for holding court in the district or within a particular part of the district, for former provisions relating to residence of one of the district judges for the District of Kansas."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsecs. (d), (e). Act ","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1954-02-10"},"text":"Feb. 10, 1954","children":[],"tail":", struck out subsecs. (d) and (e) which related to residence of one of the district judges for the Southern District of California and one of the district judges for the Southern District of Texas."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1949—Subsecs. (c) to (e). Act ","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1949-08-03"},"text":"Aug. 3, 1949","children":[],"tail":", added subsecs. (c) to (e)."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"role":"crossHeading","topic":"statutoryNotes","id":"id5236ff67-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"b","attrib":{},"text":"Statutory Notes and Related Subsidiaries","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"effectiveDateOfAmendment","id":"id5236ff68-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Effective Date of 1971 Amendment","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Amendment by ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/92/208"},"text":"Pub. L. 92–208","children":[],"tail":" effective 120 days after "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1971-12-18"},"text":"Dec. 18, 1971","children":[],"tail":", see "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/92/208/s3/f"},"text":"section 3(f) of Pub. L. 92–208","children":[],"tail":", set out as a note under "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s98"},"text":"section 98 of this title","children":[],"tail":"."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"effectiveDateOfAmendment","id":"id5236ff69-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Effective Date of 1959 Amendment","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Amendment by ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/86/3"},"text":"Pub. L. 86–3","children":[],"tail":" effective on admission of Hawaii into the Union, see Effective Date of 1959 Amendment note set out under "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s133"},"text":"section 133 of this title","children":[],"tail":". Admission of Hawaii into the Union was accomplished "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1959-08-21"},"text":"Aug. 21, 1959","children":[],"tail":", upon issuance of Proc. No. 3309, "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1959-08-21"},"text":"Aug. 21, 1959","children":[],"tail":", 25 F.R. 6868, 73 Stat. c74, as required by sections 1 and 7(c) of "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/86/3"},"text":"Pub. L. 86–3","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1959-03-18"},"text":"Mar. 18, 1959","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/73/4"},"text":"73 Stat. 4","children":[],"tail":", set out as notes preceding "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t48/s491"},"text":"section 491 of Title 48","children":[],"tail":", Territories and Insular Possessions."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"miscellaneous","id":"id5236ff6a-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Tenure and Salary Rights of Judges in Puerto Rico in Office on ","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1966-09-12"},"text":"September 12, 1966","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/89/571/s4"},"text":"Pub. L. 89–571, § 4","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1966-09-12"},"text":"Sept. 12, 1966","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/80/764"},"text":"80 Stat. 764","children":[],"tail":", provided that: "},{"tag":"quotedContent","attrib":{"origin":"/us/pl/89/571/s4"},"text":"“The amendments made by this section to sections 134 and 373 of title 28, United States Code, shall not affect the tenure of office or right to continue to receive salary after resignation, retirement, or failure of reappointment of any district judge for the district of Puerto Rico who is in office on the date of enactment of this Act [","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1966-09-12"},"text":"Sept. 12, 1966","children":[],"tail":"].”"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"miscellaneous","id":"id5236ff6b-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Applicability of Orders Under 1954 Amendment","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1954-02-10/ch6/s2/b/13/b"},"text":"Act Feb. 10, 1954, ch. 6, § 2(b)(13)(b)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/68/12"},"text":"68 Stat. 12","children":[],"tail":", provided: "},{"tag":"quotedContent","attrib":{"origin":"/us/act/1954-02-10/ch6/s2/b/13/b"},"text":"“Orders made by the judicial councils of the circuits under the second sentence of subsection (c) of ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t28/s134"},"text":"section 134 of Title 28","children":[],"tail":", as amended by this section, determining that a specified district judge shall maintain his abode at or near a place or within an area which the council has theretofore designated for the abode of a district judge under the first sentence of such subsection, shall be applicable only to district judges appointed after the enactment of this act ["},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1954-02-10"},"text":"Feb. 10, 1954","children":[],"tail":"].”"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":null}
